preferred-citation:
  type: article
  title: "SENTINEL: A Mid-Reasoning Interception Framework for Auditing Medical AI Agents in Production"
  authors:
    - family-names: Espira
      given-names: Andrew
      orcid: https://orcid.org/0009-0002-9196-8094
      affiliation: "Kustode; Department of Data Science, Saint Peter's University"
      email: andrew@kustode.com
  year: 2026
  abstract: >
    Medical AI agents can reason incorrectly faster than humans can
    intervene. SENTINEL is a mid-reasoning interception framework that
    audits agent reasoning traces before irreversible healthcare decisions
    execute, evaluating evidence quality across four dimensions
    (completeness, currency, weighting, contradiction) and gating actions
    through three tiers: auto-proceed, notify-proceed, and escalate.
    Evaluated on 950 agent reasoning traces across three agent types in a
    production healthcare revenue cycle management platform, SENTINEL
    achieves a 55/18/27% green/yellow/red tier distribution, P99 audit
    latency of 15,006 ms, and identifies 9.3% of traces with evidence
    quality issues that the agents' own confidence scores do not flag.
    Critically, SENTINEL detected 249 security-relevant reasoning events
    (PHI exposure, unsafe failover suggestions, unsupervised
    treatment-affecting decisions) that no existing agent self-confidence
    mechanism surfaces.
